<br>
The simple fact is that the hippo metaphor is not perfectly accurate and it leads me to believe that Chukzombi is right. You see when you start the game of Hungry Hippos all the marbles are in the centre.<br>
<br>
This is not true of EverQuest. If you take the analogy that each and every marble is a spawn then some of the marbles wont go in till a pre-ordained moment. Not having a guild I don't know the spawn time on the tops mobs but lets work on a mob that spawns once every three days.<br>
<br>
At the beginning of the week the marble is in the pot. There are 2 other marbles for that spawn which are not in the pot. These marbles will not go in till day three and day six of the week. These marbles will not go in any sooner and therefore cannot be swallowed by the hippos beforehand.<br>
<br>
So a player which decides to take the free marbles beside the game, namely ring quests, ToT practice, and so on will never be in a situation where come day 3 they have already been beaten to the punch. In fact the hippo can take free marbles until day 6 when he can still go for the special marble mentioned earlier. Or a player can go for the special marble first and take the rest of the week taking free marbles.<br>
<br>
The simple fact is that a guild could technically spend all the week on free marbles. Since each encounter takes a certain amount of time the amount of marbles a hippo can eat is finite. A hippo going after special marbles will not get any more then a hippo eating free marbles. In fact given that there is little competition for the free marbles a guild that goes after special marbles only is going to eat less.<br>
<br>
The problem only comes when two hippos go after the same marble, at the same time, and both refuse to back down. The problem is that certain hippos regard certain marbles as easy marbles and refuse to do anything as clever as going after those free marbles which reap rewards just as great as the special ones.<br>
<br>
But the main problem is when one hippo refuses to show any sort of respect for any other hippo. Which sadly, we see time and time again.<br>
